Heil wants to test other industries after meat industry
The COVID-19 crisis brought conditions in parts of the meat industry back to light.
Stricter laws are imminent.
But are they right - and will it stay that way?
Federal Minister of Labour Hubertus Heil (SPD) wants to review other sectors after the now planned strict regulations against abuses in the meat industry.
" We will look at industry by industry and then take appropriate measures for the respective industry if necessary, " said Heil to the German Press Agency in Berlin.
Germany's employers are already warning against restricting work contracts in general.
After the massive corona outbreak at the meat giant Tönnies in North Rhine-Westphalia, the Federal Cabinet wants to pass a law of salvation this Wednesday.
Large-scale slaughterhouses should no longer be allowed to employ third-party personnel for slaughter, cutting and meat processing.
To this end, the use of contract workers and temporary workers is to be banned there.
Employer president Ingo Kramer told dpa: " Stay away from a general restriction on work contracts and temporary employment if you don't want to completely choke off the economy. "
Contracts for work and services are, for example, the imperative basis for creating added value for customers in wide areas of the trades, the construction industry and plant construction.
" The failings of individuals cannot destroy such an important instrument. "
Heil assured: " My goal is not to ban contracts for work and services everywhere in the German economy. "
Contracts for work and services make sense.
" If an industrial company commissions a craftsman to install a security system, this is a completely normal work contract. "
The German meat industry considers a ban on work contracts and temporary agency work in its sector alone unconstitutional.
It cannot be explained why different labour law should apply to the portioning and packaging of cheese in the future than to sausages, it says in a statement on the proposed law, as reported by the " Neue Osnabrücker Zeitung " (Saturday).
In the event of a ban, the consumer price would rise by 10 to 20 percent per kilo and product.
According to the results of an examination by the North Rhine-Westphalia Occupational Safety and Health Administration, many Eastern European employees from work contract companies worked in the industry, sometimes 16 hours a day.
Often they had no rest.
Salary was withheld for protective equipment or rent.
It was also noted that the housing situation for workers was often miserable.
Heil said that a relatively harsh law had already entered into force for the meat industry in 2017.
However, these were circumvented by " tricky constructions. "
" Now we have to clean up fundamentally. "
The politician announced: " The Occupational Safety and Health Act, which we want to pass in the cabinet at the end of July, also includes measures that not only affect the meat industry - for example, higher testing rates for occupational safety and health or clear criteria for communal accommodation. "
The draft presented to dpa includes amendments to the Act on the Protection of Workers' Rights in the Meat Industry and the Occupational Safety and Health Act.
Brandenburg's Minister for Consumer Protection, Ursula Nonnemacher (Green Party), considers more intensive controls necessary.
" I would like us to be able to carry out even more inspections in many supervisory areas: food inspections, animal welfare, everything possible, including animal transport, for example, " said Nonnemacher on Sunday in the RBB broadcast " Brandenburg aktuell. "
But for more checks, more staff positions are also needed.
