Baden-Württemberg: Over 250 illegal car races recorded
Stuttgart - Despite all threatened penalties and court rulings, motorists continue to step on the gas in countless illegal races on the roads of Baden-Württemberg: Last year and the first four months of this year, the police in the southwest have already registered more than 250 illegal car races.
There are no comparative values for the years before, but the racers are increasingly making work for the judicial authorities: At the public prosecutor's offices between Konstanz and Mannheim, a total of 155 investigations into illegal races were conducted in 2018, a year later there were already 252 and in the current year by the beginning of June already 151.
The races were less about organized events, as can be seen from the response of the Ministry of the Interior to an inquiry by the Landtag-SPD.
In most cases, the drivers competed against each other spontaneously or they had fled from the police - this is also reported as an illegal race.
At the wheel were mainly German men between the ages of 18 and 60.
113 fines - 15 times imprisonment
Only in comparatively few cases are the racers caught and also asked to pay: According to the Ministry of the Interior, a total of 113 fines have been imposed and 15 prison sentences pronounced since 2018.
However, there are no indications that the number of illegal car races is actually increasing.
Rather, because of the numerous tragic accidents and trials of previous years, other drivers reacted more sensitively than before and reported more frequently, said a ministry spokesman.
Autobahn 8 is particularly popular with racers. Again and again, drivers brake the traffic there to make room for themselves and use the free track for a race.
Last August, a dozen drivers were caught near Kirchheim unter Teck, three months earlier there were even 18 drivers on the A8 near Merklingen.
A81 is the most popular " racetrack "
On the A81, the police even registered more races than on any other federal highway.
With a speed limit, an attempt is being made there to slow down the racers on the particularly affected section between Engen and Geisingen.
The mostly high-priced and pimped-up sports and luxury cars often have Swiss license plates, because the drivers move to the lawn in Germany because of the high penalties for driving too fast and car racing in the neighboring country.
For the SPD, the speed limit must not be reduced to a few routes: " With a general speed limit of 130 kilometers per hour, we would get rid of this problem on motorways, " says Martin Rivoir, the traffic expert of the SPD parliamentary group.
" The inhibition threshold for racers would be significantly higher if one were not allowed to travel legally here and there at 200 kilometres per hour and more. "
Rivoir thinks less of education or image campaigns: " Anyone who ignores all rules in such a way and puts at risk not only their own lives, but also the lives of other road users, is hardly reachable with reason. "
ADAC calls for stronger police crackdown
For the ADAC, on the other hand, this is not enough: " We assume that racers will not be deterred by the speed limits, " says Holger Bach, Head of Transport and Environment at ADAC Württemberg.
He calls for additional and also tougher controls on the affected routes.
Not infrequently, the high-speed trial of strength turns into painful and momentous seriousness: Since January 2019 and until April 2020, three people across the country have died in the races, two of them bystanders in a nightly crash in downtown Stuttgart and one in Gerlingen.
Two young men are said to have delivered a car race there in November.
One of the vehicles came off the road, crashed into a garden wall and remained lying on the side, the 18-year-old co-driver died.
21 more people were injured in the races of the past two years.
However, in the opinion of Minister of the Interior Thomas Strobl, stricter penalties are not necessary: " Legislative action to sanction illegal motor vehicle races more severely is not seen, " says the paper of the Ministry of the Interior.
