Fleetwood Mac co-founder Peter Green died
His life was like a rollercoaster ride: After a rapid ascent with Fleetwood Mac, it went steeply downhill and then slowly uphill again.
Now the blues rock guitarist Peter Green has died at the age of 73.
Ingenious guitarist, drug junkie, cult fan: The co-founder of the band Fleetwood Mac, Peter Green, is dead.
He died peacefully in his sleep at the age of 73, informed family members on Saturday in an official statement, a further statement would be announced for the next few days.
Top musicians like Peter Frampton praised Green as one of the best blues and rock guitarists.
Mick Fleetwood spoke in an emotional reaction of a " monumental loss " for all past and present members of the band Fleetwood Mac.
The drummer Fleetwood and the guitarist Green had founded the now long-legendary band in London in 1967, his dreamy instrumental hit " Albatross " remains unforgotten to this day.
The musician's life (" The End Of The Game, " " In The Skies ") resembled a rollercoaster ride.
With Fleetwood Mac, Green experienced a rapid rise - the band celebrated their greatest successes but then without him.
There is said to have been a dispute, among other things, because Green wanted to donate all of the group's profits to charity.
He began to perform in wide robes and with a large crucifix.
Psychological problems are also said to have played a role.
Already three years after the foundation Green left the band in 1970.
A social decline followed.
The blues rock guitarist suffered from drug abuse and schizophrenia, as biographers reported.
For a long time, Green was treated in psychiatry.
During much of the 1970s, the musician disappeared from the scene.
He is said to have temporarily lived on the street, worked as a cemetery gardener and spent some time in an Israeli kibbutz.
Green was born in 1946 to a Jewish working-class family in the London borough of Bethnal Green.
Already at a young age he was enthusiastic about US blues musicians such as B.B. King and Muddy Waters.
At the age of eleven he learned his first guitar chords.
At the age of 15, the teenager began to play the guitar professionally and five years later got the chance to stand on stage as lead guitarist for the instrumental band Peter B's Looners.
A little later he was engaged as a replacement for his idol Eric Clapton at the Bluesbreakers.
In the midst of the blues boom, Green founded Fleetwood Mac in the summer of 1967 together with his Bluesbreakers colleagues Mick Fleetwood and John McVie.
The song " Albatross, " composed by Green, brought the group their first number one hit in the winter of 1968 / 69 and catapulted them to the top of the British music scene.
But the rapid rise soon showed its downsides: Green could not cope with the media hype, his experiments with the drug LSD became more and more extreme.
He later commented on life between music and addiction in an interview: " The worst thing that happened to me in life are the drugs - the best thing was to land a number 1 hit. "
Towards the end of the decade, Green surprisingly achieved a respectable success in 1979 with an album inspired by religious themes.
Fleetwood Mac meanwhile swam without him in a new formation on a wave of success.
Their 1977 album " Rumours " sold more than 40 million copies worldwide.
Despite various small solo successes, Green did not make a major comeback until he went new to the start in 1996 with a group of musician friends.
The British " Daily Telegraph " spoke at the time of a rock star who had returned to earth.
Free of drugs, Green released several albums with the Peter Green Splinter Group until the band disbanded in 2004.
For music experts, he was already a blues legend during his lifetime - and with his gentle sound, one of the most influential guitarists of the past decades.
